show awards,
culminating at Westminster.

06:17.043 --> 06:18.812 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Go for C.J.

06:18.912 --> 06:23.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
top senators
weigh in on the next Supreme
Court nominee;

06:23.950 --> 06:30.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
should Apple grant law
enforcement access
to iPhone data?; political
charges and countercharges

06:30.357 --> 06:36.129 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fly in South Carolina; and much
more.

06:36.229 --> 06:50.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The passing of
Justice Antonin
Scalia has unleashed a political
battle of

06:50.644 --> 06:56.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
epic proportions that is
reverberating from
the campaign trail to Capitol
Hill. President

06:56.116 --> 07:01.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obama has made it clear he will
nominate someone.
But, in the Senate, most
Republicans say he

07:02.022 --> 07:04.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shouldn't, and, if he does, they
won't confirm.

07:04.891 --> 07:09.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We hear now from two senior
members of the
Senate Judiciary Committee,
which first considers

07:09.863 --> 07:11.665 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
any nominee.

07:11.765 --> 07:17.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First up, Democratic Senator
Dianne Feinstein
of California. She joins us from
San Francisco.

07:17.370 --> 07:19.139 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome, Senator Feinstein.

07:19.239 --> 07:22.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what is your response to
your Republican
colleagues who say this should
be left to

07:22.842 --> 07:24.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the next president?

07:24.344 --> 07:27.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. DIANNE FEINSTEIN (D),
California: Well,
I would say this, Judy.

07:27.113 --> 07:34.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fourteen nominees have been
confirmed in the
final year of a presidency in
history. And,

07:34.187 --> 07:40.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a matter of fact, Ronald
Reagan presented
Judge Kennedy to become Justice
Kennedy, and

07:40.593 --> 07:45.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he became that and was confirmed
in the last
year of Reagan's administration.

07:45.498 --> 07:53.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it is a well-established
fact that this
can happen. I mean, I remember
back. One of

07:53.473 --> 08:01.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my very first confirmation
hearings was Justice
Ginsburg. And both the chairman
of the committee

08:01.448 --> 08:07.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
today, Senator Grassley and
Senator Hatch,
voted for her. And I remember
their statements

08:07.520 --> 08:15.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to this day about a president
being entitled
to his nominees, provided they
were qualified,

08:15.729 --> 08:23.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
provided they had the requisite
skills, the
integrity, the moral compass to
be enacted.

08:23.670 --> 08:30.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they both voted for Justice
Ginsburg.
I wish we could go back to those
days, because

08:30.276 --> 08:34.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what's happening now is very
destructive of
the process.

08:34.381 --> 08:39.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me just
cite quickly
what Senator Hatch has said. And
I'm going

08:39.252 --> 08:43.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be talking to him in just a
minute. He
said the Senate has never
allowed a term-limited

08:43.890 --> 08:47.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
president to nominate someone
this late in
his term.

08:47.560 --> 08:54.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. DIANNE FEINSTEIN: Well, the
record reflects
that 14 have been confirmed in
the final year.

08:54.434 --> 08:57.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're well able to do it in the
time that
remains.

08:57.871 --> 09:04.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, why not do it? Because what
is left are
several very important cases,
whereby, if

09:04.944 --> 09:12.385 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there is a tie vote, the
appellate court decision
takes precedence, therefore,
shorting the

09:12.485 --> 09:18.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
justice system for whoever it
was that was
on the other side of the
appellate court decision.

09:18.958 --> 09:24.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we shouldn't do that. That,
I think, is
destructive to what is, you
know, a very well-put-together

09:25.098 --> 09:27.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
system of justice.

09:27.133 --> 09:30.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just quickly, two
other questions.
Republicans say it was the
Democrats who politicized

09:30.804 --> 09:35.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this process with the way they
went after
Robert Bork, the way they went
after Clarence

09:35.508 --> 09:37.410 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thomas, that the Democrats
started this.

09:37.510 --> 09:42.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. DIANNE FEINSTEIN: Yes,
well, I wasn't
here then, so I really can't
comment.

09:42.749 --> 09:49.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But whoever it was, it seems to
me the time
has come to end it. And I had
hoped that we

09:49.255 --> 09:57.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were in the process of ending
it. We have
confirmed 11 judges last year.
We have 78

09:57.263 --> 10:03.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pending. And it shouldn't be
that way. And,
you know, Barack Obama has
almost a full year

10:03.803 --> 10:09.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
left. Are you saying then that
his hands could
be -- should be handcuffed and
that he can't

10:09.442 --> 10:13.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
make appointments in that full
year of his
presidency?

10:13.880 --> 10:20.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's a mistake. And
one thing, one
more thing. What goes around
comes around.

10:20.353 --> 10:26.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I re-read Orrin Hatch's
statement after
the Ginsburg hearing. And
regardless of what

10:26.292 --> 10:30.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has happened since then, I think
he was absolutely
right.

10:30.330 --> 10:37.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the ability to process a
nominee becomes
very important and I think very
significant.

10:37.203 --> 10:40.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would hope that Orrin
would remember
that.

10:40.106 --> 10:45.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, Senator
Feinstein,
how far to the center should the
president

10:45.311 --> 10:51.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lean in choosing a nominee?
Should he try
hard to find somebody who is
going to appeal

10:51.417 --> 10:53.620 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to Republicans, as well as
Democrats?

10:53.720 --> 10:58.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. DIANNE FEINSTEIN: Well, I
think the answer
to that question is yes, if you
want to get

10:58.358 --> 11:04.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
someone confirmed, I think
somebody that has
gone through the confirmation
process -- and

11:04.764 --> 11:11.037 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there are several who are
well-qualified on
that score -- or somebody that
would be seen

11:11.137 --> 11:14.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as outstanding by both sides of
the aisle.

11:14.807 --> 11:20.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if either one of those were
to happen,
I think the chances of
confirmation would

11:20.446 --> 11:22.115 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be very high.

11:22.215 --> 11:25.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Senator Dianne
Feinstein joining
us from California, we thank
you.

11:25.885 --> 11:28.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SEN. DIANNE FEINSTEIN: Thank
you, Judy.

11:28.121 --> 11:33.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now to a
Republican view,
Senator Orrin Hatch of Utah.
He's also on

11:33.226 --> 11:37.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Judiciary Committee, and he
joins us from
Salt Lake City.

11:37.163 --> 11:42.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Welcome, Senator Hatch. So the
Republicans
are in the majority. The
president has said

11:42.168 --> 11:48.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he is going to nominate someone
to fill the
term or to take the place of
Justice Scalia.

11:48.474 --> 11:50.276 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What is going to happen then?

11:50.376 --> 11:54.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. ORRIN HATCH (R), Utah:
Well, the president
has an absolute right to
nominate whoever

11:54.314 --> 11:57.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he wants to. And I would vote to
protect that
right.

11:57.850 --> 12:03.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the Senate also has an
absolute right
to confirm or not to confirm.
And so I do

12:03.790 --> 12:10.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support Senator McConnell in
saying, but,
look, let's get it out of this
terrible presidential

12:10.630 --> 12:15.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
brouhaha that is going on, and
let's get it
over to the next year, and be
fair to both

12:15.702 --> 12:19.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sides, because what would happen
is whoever
