46:00.891 --> 46:05.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the many elements both seen and
unseen that
go into filmmaking.

46:05.630 --> 46:07.632 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One of those is the musical
score.

46:07.732 --> 46:12.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown visited
Oscar-nominated film
composer Carter Burwell recently
in his New

46:13.070 --> 46:18.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
York studio to see how he
creates the soundtracks
to the movies.

46:18.976 --> 46:26.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's one of the
elements of
film that often goes unnoticed,
unless it's

46:26.751 --> 46:32.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very bad, or, in the case of
"Carol," very
good, the musical score.

46:32.723 --> 46:37.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARTER BURWELL, Composer: You
know, I think
of that theme as being about the
heart-beating

46:37.728 --> 46:46.070 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
excitement and mystery of seeing
someone and
feeling that tug.

46:46.170 --> 46:52.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Carter Burwell
has been composing
music for movies for more than
30 years. And

46:52.910 --> 46:57.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the first time, he's been
nominated for
an Oscar for his work on the
film directed

46:57.114 --> 47:01.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by Todd Haynes about two women
falling in
love in postwar America.

47:01.652 --> 47:07.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARTER BURWELL: I don't want
there to be music
in the scene, or in the film,
just because

47:07.158 --> 47:11.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's expected, I want it to be
there to say
something, and ideally to say
something that

47:12.063 --> 47:14.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you wouldn't otherwise -- that
wouldn't otherwise
be said.

47:14.799 --> 47:20.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, "Carol" is a perfect
example of
this, because it's very sparse
for dialogue

47:20.638 --> 47:27.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to begin with, and also it's a
love story
between two women at a time when
that actually

47:27.878 --> 47:29.180 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
couldn't be spoken of openly.

47:29.280 --> 47:30.981 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Literally
unspoken.

47:31.082 --> 47:34.752 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CARTER BURWELL: Literally
unspoken. And the
music is saying a lot that the
characters

47:34.852 --> 47:36.654 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
either can't or won't say.

47:36.754 --> 47:42.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: A one-time
architecture student
and punk rocker, Burwell has
composed music

47:42.126 --> 47:48.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for more than 80 films,
beginning with the
Coen brothers' "Blood Simple" in
1984.

47:48.432 --> 47:56.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since then, he's done most of
their major
films, including the
just-released "Hail,

47:56.574 --> 48:08.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Caesar!." He's also worked on
commercial giants,
like the "Twilight" saga, and
this year composed

48:08.686 --> 48:20.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
music for the Oscar-nominated
stop-motion
picture "Anomalisa."

48:20.164 --> 48:24.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Burwell often begins by reading
a script to
determine, with the director,
what kind of

48:24.635 --> 48:27.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
music, if any, might be
appropriate.

48:27.505 --> 48:32.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARTER BURWELL: If it is early
in the process,
we can have a conversation that
at least suggests

48:32.676 --> 48:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what type of instrumentation
there might be.
In other words, how expensive
might this music

48:36.747 --> 48:39.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be? Is there going to be a
symphony orchestra?
Is it going to be a guy with a
ukulele?

48:39.550 --> 48:42.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Wait a minute. So
that's the
first thing, is how expensive it
is, not the

48:42.720 --> 48:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- what are we looking for here,
what kind
of sound, what kind of...

48:47.191 --> 48:52.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARTER BURWELL: Well, you know,
they go hand
in hand, but, early on,
honestly, figuring

48:52.396 --> 48:56.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out the budget is -- especially,
you know,
I work on a lot of low-budget
films, and squeezing

48:56.867 --> 48:59.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
everything and fitting it as
tightly as you
can is important.

49:00.004 --> 49:05.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: He doesn't begin
writing music
until he watches early cuts of
the scenes,

49:05.543 --> 49:12.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
using visual cues, the look the
director is
after, to determine his musical
ones.

49:12.550 --> 49:17.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the case of "Carol," he
created individual
instrumental voices, both
woodwinds, for the

49:17.855 --> 49:19.623 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
